The Bitcoin "hodl tax" is starting to happen! 👀 

Customers of custodial Bitcoin service Swan are being charged up to a $125 "admin fee" by their custodian partner.

Almost 5 months ago I predicted this would start happening after a Bitcoin Magazine op ed talked about introducing a "hodl tax" at the protocol level. I predicted this wouldn't happen at the protocol, but institutions would pass it on to the consumer.

It makes sense: if no one can transact on Bitcoin, someone has to pay mining fees. If people are using custodial services, which do have to pay miners to move funds around periodically, they'll pay the high fees, but they have to get them back from somewhere.

No such thing as a free lunch, and users will pay for Bitcoin's security, whether they like it or not!

And yes: they did just recreate the banking system, complete with regular fees!

Better just make it open and transparent and add a tail emission, or let users transact affordable on the base layer. Either way they wouldn't be beholden to centralized third parties that can rug or add usurious fees on a whim.

Peer-to-peer digital cash is still a thing. It's just not the banking 2.0 that Bitcoin has become.
